On 8 Apr 1994 18:39:01 GMT, davep@paladin.corp.sgi.com (David Packer) said:

> I think one thing to note, is that even though Unix systems are more
> difficult to "muck" with the kernel. Who says that the kernel needs to be
> mucked for a virus to take effect?? Any root ran process has full system
> access therefore allowing the ability of viruses to be implemented.

I'm not sure that is a virus. First of all, if you set your permissions
properly, then root programs cannot be modified (you are right, now all
systems do this). Even better is to implement the notion of least privilege,
and to remove what is special about ID=0. But those are not viruses, IMHO.

Daniel
